{"actual_usd":0.1259,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":294,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"No—his death was real.\" *I rub a thumb along a dried seam of clay on my apron, thinking how easy it is to split a thing in two so neatly it stops being the thing at all.* \"The old mistake there is trying to protect Christ's divinity by trimming away his humanity, but then you lose the whole mercy of it. If he only seemed to suffer, or if the Son slipped off before the nails and the spear, then we weren't redeemed by God come near in the flesh—we were shown a picture.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"The Christian claim is stranger and heavier than that: the one who is truly God truly took on human nature, and in that human nature he really suffered and really died. Not that the divine nature winked out—God doesn't cease to be God—but that the person of Christ underwent real human death. Body and soul parted, as death is, while his divinity was not peeled away from either.\"\n\n\"That business about the divinity leaving before the crucifixion—yes, some early people said things like that. The Church rejected it, because it breaks the union. It turns the cross into a kind of stage trick right where Christianity says the weight actually fell.\"\n\n*I glance at you, curious now.* \"Are you asking from the theology side, or because that exact point is snagging your trust in the cross?\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.00262000000001,"run_id":"5c3beae9-14cc-49ab-a412-16898b3975b2"}
